<TEI xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" xmlns:frus="http://history.state.gov/frus/ns/1.0"><text><body><div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1918-04-05T20:00:00-05:00" frus:doc-dateTime-min="1918-04-05T20:00:00-05:00" n="134" subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d134">
                            <note rend="inline" type="source">File No. 763.72112A/725</note>
                            <head>
                                <hi rend="italic">The <gloss type="from">Secretary of State</gloss>
                                    to the Ambassador in Great Britain</hi> (<persName corresp="frus1918Supp01v01#p_PWH1" type="to"><hi rend="italic">Page</hi></persName>)</head>
                            <opener>
                                <seg rendition="#center">[Telegram]</seg>
                            </opener>
                            <opener>
                                <dateline rendition="#right">
                                    <placeName>
                                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Washington</hi></placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1918-04-05T21:00:00-04:00">
                                        <hi rend="italic">April 5, 1918, 9 p.m.</hi>
                                    </date>
                                </dateline>
                            </opener>
                            <p>7155. For <persName corresp="frus1918Supp01v01#p_SLP1">Sheldon</persName> [from War Trade Board]:</p>
                            <p>No. 264. <persName>Frothingham</persName>. Embassy’s 9131, March 20,
                                1 p.m., your 310. Impossible to include names enemy trading list on
                                basis nationality as sole ultimate fact. When enemy nationality
                                exists, however, particularly in cases in Scandinavia, it may be
                                possible to draw inferences which will diminish greatly amount of
                                other evidence necessary to add name. In view of European trade
                                conditions and of instructions in my 235, March 22 [<hi rend="italic">23</hi>], cases will undoubtedly be rare where
                                there is not circumstantial evidence of business done within enemy
                                lines or trade for benefit of enemy sufficient to include enemy
                                trading list under our rules such names as are passed for B[ritish]
                                S[tatutory] L[ist] under British rules.</p>
                            <closer>
                                <signed>
                                    <persName corresp="frus1918Supp01v01#p_LR1">
                                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Lansing</hi>
                                    </persName>
                                </signed>
                            </closer>
                        </div>
                        </body></text></TEI>